		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">It put out SMS, MD, CD, 32X, Saturn, and Dreamcast, in the same time that the other company put out only three consoles.</div><br />To me it seems like SEGA thought they'd have some sort of advantage if they jumped to the next generation before everyone else. Maybe because it actually worked with the Genesis (its only actually successful console) when they first tried it, so they just kept trying to do the same thing over and over again, only to come up with a series of failed accessories and consoles. They made some pretty bad decisions.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">And I don't think Nintendo claimed exclusivity</div><br />I don't know what the deal with the games that were in fact released on multiple platforms (including the NES) is, but it seems Nintendo forced its licensed third-party developers to keep games exclusive to the NES for 2 years: <a href="http://www.nesplayer.com/features/lawsuits/tengen.htm" class="postlink">link 1</a>, <a href="http://digital-law-online.info/cases/24PQ2D1015.htm" class="postlink">link 2</a>.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">mic_ wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I never cared much for the Game Gear, but at least some developers knew how to <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KXwOlTyLoco" class="postlink">get the most out of it</a>.</div>
<br />That game is amazing... it's like the 8 sprites per scanline limitation doesn't exist (the person that made the video didn't disable it on the emulator, right? <img src="./images/smilies/icon_eek.gif" alt=":shock:" title="Shocked" />)! EDIT: I played the game and indeed that video was made with the sprite limit disabled. The game is still interesting, but not as impressive.
<br />
<br />Since this topic is about the GB after all, does anyone know of anything remotely similar for it? What are the best examples of impressive GB games?

		

