	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">tokumaru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Movie buffs might disagree.</div><br />How often do movie buffs start watching the exact same movie after it ends?</div><br />Four words for kids: Beauty and the Beast.<br />Four words for grown-ups: Rocky Horror Picture Show.<br />Two more words: Hampster Dance.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Games are different every time you play because of their interactivity, which means they can usually keep people interested much longer than non-interactive activities can.</div>
<br />As I pointed out years ago on forum.gbadev.org, it's too bad rhythm games like DDR and Guitar Hero are patented. Otherwise, it'd be fairly easy to turn a demo that doesn't use all the sprites into a game by putting a plane of arrows in front of the effects and then changing the demo effects based on the player's accuracy.
<br />
<br />But I understand your thesis: capabilities exposed by the demoscene in its abstract music videos aren't very well correlated with capabilities required by a wide range of video game genres.

		

		</td>
